node.text:
This long-legged critter is an arrow crab also known as a spider crab!

They have a triangle-shaped body and extended “snout”, and can be a multitude of colors. Symbiotic relationships have been observed between arrow crabs and squirrelfish and moray eels. Crabs are usually the main food for moray eels and squirrelfish so the relationship was surprising to researchers. The arrow crab species Stenorhynchus seticornis has been seen cleaning several species of moray eels and squirrelfish, and researchers believe other species of reef fish may be potential “clients” too.
​

node.text:
This adorable creature is a red panda!

Mostly found in the high-altitude forests of the eastern Himalayas and central China, this typically solitary animal is only slightly bigger than a domestic cat but with a long bushy tail that helps it balance in trees. Even though it shares a name with a certain giant bear, it’s actually a member of its own family, the Ailuridae, and is likely more closely related to skunks, raccoons, and weasels.

Only 10,000 mature individuals are said to remain in the wild due to habitat destruction. 

Image credit: Hyserb/Shutterstock, Jose Angel Astor Rocha/Shutterstock, AB Photographie/Shutterstock

node.text:
Foxes have the incredible ability to catch their rodent prey even when those mice are scurrying below a blanket of snow. These foxes use their sharp sense of hearing to track down the mice, and strike headfirst into the snow at the right moment.

Surprisingly, foxes can also sense the magnetic field of the earth and use that to help them catch their prey. A study found that a fox’s hunt is successful more than 70% of the time when it’s lined up with a certain magnetic field direction, facing northeast, whereas when it’s not pointed this way, its success rate drops to 18%.

Happy #MicrobeMonday! Take a look at this stunning microscopic diatom as it goes about its business. These single-celled organisms can be found wherever there’s water. Diatoms get their energy from photosynthesis, releasing oxygen as a byproduct. Their particularly long cell walls are made of pure silica, which is the same chemical compound found in glass!
​

node.text:
Despite incredible advances, some cancers remain incurable. Whether it be onslaught by radiation, cell destruction via chemotherapy, or targeted drug therapies to halt tumor growth, some cancers are simply resistant to all weapons scientists use against them. 

One such cancer is metastatic estrogen receptor-positive breast cancer. This aggressive form of breast cancer is the most common form of breast cancer, yet some cases are entirely incurable due to various mutations that can make it resistant to treatment. 

However, scientists may have discovered a new weakness – and it’s a big one. 

In a recent study published in Science Translational Medicine, researchers from the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign outline a new compound that directly targets human metastatic breast cancer cells and all their metastases (secondary growths around the body as a result of the cancer spreading) in mice, resulting in almost complete tumor regression.
​
​Read the full story by hitting this image post via the link in our bio.  📖

Meet the eastern tiger swallowtail butterfly! Papilio glaucus is native to eastern North America, and found anywhere east of the Mississippi river to the Great Plains states.

The male is yellow with black ‘tiger stripes’ on the wings, and the female is either yellow or black, making them dimorphic. The yellow morph has a band of blue spots along the hindwing, and the dark morph is almost fully black.

The eastern tiger swallowtail butterfly is the state butterfly of Alabama, Delaware, Georgia, North Carolina and South Carolina. Beautiful!

Image credit: John Reed Pavan / Shutterstock, J. Marquardt / Shutterstock

node.text:
Look at this little guy! The Kentish plovers (Charadrius alexandrinus) are a type of small shorebird from the family Charadriidae, which weigh a mere 40-44g, with a length of 16cm, and a wingspan of 44 cm. These birds typically have pale plumes with a white underside, greyish brown legs, and a dark bill.

They breed on the shores of lakes, lagoons, and sandy beaches, and when it comes to courtship displays, the Kentish plovers scrape at the ground to form small cavities where they build nests, and fight to defend their breeding territories. Oh, and in case you didn't notice, the chicks are unbelievably cute!
